06401nam a22008175i 9781575065854DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750658547 a10.1515/97815750658542doi  a(DE-B1597)583711  a(OCoLC)1266228198  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04aThe Pentateuch as Torah :bNew Models for Understanding Its Promulgation and Acceptance /ced. by Bernard M. Levinson, Gary N. Knoppers. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tHow, When, Where, and Why Did the Pentateuch Become the Torah? -- tPart 1. Ratifying Local Law Codes in an International Age -- tThe Persian Imperial Authorization as a Historical Problem and as a Biblical Construct: A Plea for Distinctions in the Current Debate -- tThe Rise of Torah -- tLocal Law in an Imperial Context: The Role of Torah in the (Imagined) Persian Period -- tTemple and Torah: Reflections on the Legal Status of the Pentateuch between Elephantine and Qumran -- tThe Pentateuch in Ancient Mediterranean Context: The Publication of Local Lawcodes -- tPart 2. Prophets, Polemics, and Publishers: The Growing Importance of Writing in Persian Period Judah -- tFrom History Writing to Library Building: The End of History and the Birth of the Book -- tScribal Scholarship in the Formation of Torah and Prophets: A Postexilic Scribal Debate between Priestly Scholarship and Literary Prophecy- The Example of the Book of Jeremiah and Its Relation to the Pentateuch -- tPart 3. The Torah as a Foundational Document in Judah and Samaria -- tThe Torah between Samaria and Judah: Shechem and Gerizim in Deuteronomy and Joshua -- tThe "Publication" of Legal Texts in Ancient Judah -- tThe Samaritans and Their Pentateuch -- tPart 4. The Translation, Interpretation, and Application of the Torah in Early Jewish Literature -- tThe Second Temple and the Legal Status of the Torah: The Hermeneutics of the Torah in the Books of Ruth and Ezra -- tThe Septuagint of the Pentateuch and Ptolemaic Rule -- tThe Use of the Pentateuch in the Temple Scroll and the Damascus Document in the Second Century B.C.E. -- tThe Torah as the Rhetoric of Priesthood -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture -- tIndex of Other Ancient Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince antiquity, the five books of Moses have served as a sacred constitution, foundational for both Jews and Samaritans. However long the process of accepting the Pentateuch as authoritative tōrâ ("instruction") took, this was by all accounts a monumental achievement in the history of these peoples and indeed an important moment in the history of the ancient world. In the long development of Western societies, the Pentateuch has served as a major influence on the development of law, political philosophy, and social thought. The question is: how, where, and why did this process of acceptance occur, when did it occur, and how long did it take?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJudaismxHistoryyPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.DvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aCarr, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrätz, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagedorn, Anselm C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Paul B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoppers, Gary N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoppers, Gary N., eeditor.4edt4http://i